   406‚Üí/// Prints a heuristic error messages when nothing is searched.
   407‚Üí///
   408‚Üí/// This can happen if an applicable ignore file has one or more rules that
   409‚Üí/// are too broad and cause ripgrep to ignore everything.
   410‚Üí///
   411‚Üí/// We only show this error message when the user does *not* provide an
   412‚Üí/// explicit path to search. This is because the message can otherwise be
   413‚Üí/// noisy, e.g., when it is intended that there is nothing to search.
   414‚Üífn eprint_nothing_searched() {
   415‚Üí    err_message!(
   416‚Üí        "No files were searched, which means ripgrep probably \
   417‚Üí         applied a filter you didn't expect.\n\
   418‚Üí         Running with --debug will show why files are being skipped."
   419‚Üí    );
   420‚Üí}
   421‚Üí
   422‚Üí/// Prints the statistics given to the writer given.
   423‚Üí///
   424‚Üí/// The search mode given determines whether the stats should be printed in
   425‚Üí/// a plain text format or in a JSON format.
   426‚Üí///
   427‚Üí/// The `started` time should be the time at which ripgrep started working.
   428‚Üí///
   429‚Üí/// If an error occurs while writing, then writing stops and the error is
   430‚Üí/// returned. Note that callers should probably ignore this errror, since
   431‚Üí/// whether stats fail to print or not generally shouldn't cause ripgrep to
   432‚Üí/// enter into an "error" state. And usually the only way for this to fail is
   433‚Üí/// if writing to stdout itself fails.
   434‚Üífn print_stats<W: Write>(
   435‚Üí    mode: SearchMode,
   436‚Üí    stats: &grep::printer::Stats,
